Class JSONParams

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
      • java.util.HashMap<K,V>
        • java.util.LinkedHashMap<String,JSONParamsEntry>
          • com.novartis.opensource.yada.JSONParams
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Map<String,JSONParamsEntry>

    public class JSONParams
extends LinkedHashMap<String,JSONParamsEntry>
    A LinkedHashMap implementation for storing values passed to the YADA Service, by way of YADARequest in the url parameters or http POST content. Naturally, JSONParams or j parameters map directly, but in fact, standard parameters (qname or q, and params or p) are ultimately mapped to these objects as well.

    This map contains YADA query names as keys, and JSONParamsEntry objects as values. Thus the structure is like the following:

    query : { JSONParamsEntry }

    which in turns parses out to:

    query : { DATA: [ array of data ], PARAMS: [ array of params ] }

    Since:
    0.4.0.0
    Author:
    David Varon
    See Also:
    JSONParamsEntry, Serialized Form

      • JSONParams

        public JSONParams(String jp)
           throws YADAQueryConfigurationException
        Takes a json string as an argument and converts it into a JSONParams object. The String must be a String reprentation of a JSONArray and must conform to the JSONParams specification, e.g.: [{"qname":"name of query","DATA":[{"col_1":"val_1",..."col_n":"val_n"},{...},...]}
        Parameters:
        jp - the json string to convert to an object
        Throws:
        YADAQueryConfigurationException - when the object can't be created, probably due to a malformed, or non-compliant json string.
        Since:
        0.4.0.0

      • JSONParams

        public JSONParams(String[] jp)
           throws YADAQueryConfigurationException

        Takes a String[] array as an argument and converts it into a JSONParams object.

        The jp array can contain a representation of a JSONArray, in which case only the first index of the jp param will be processed.

        Alternatively, if jp contains String representations of JSONObjects, a new JSONArray will be instantiated and populated with the objects.

        Currently, only JSON syntax checking is performed, but no YADA syntax validation against the JSONParams specification is performed.

        This is the constructor called by Service.handleRequest(javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest) when encountering a JSONParams url parameter.
        Parameters:
        jp - an array containing json strings
        Throws:
        YADAQueryConfigurationException - when jp is not convertable into a JSONParams object
        Since:
        0.4.0.0
        See Also:
        YADARequest.setJsonParams(String[]), Service.handleRequest(javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest)

      • addData

        public void addData(String qname,
           LinkedHashMap<String,String[]> data)
        Adds data, pre-conformed into a LinkedHashMap<String,String[]>, to the JSONParamsEntry in the map, associated to qname. If qname is not yet in the map, it is added first.

        Calls JSONParamsEntry.addData(LinkedHashMap) to perform the LinkedHashMap to JSONParamsEntry conversion.

        Parameters:
        qname - the query name to add to the map
        data - the data to add to the entry associated to the query in the map
        Since:
        0.4.0.0
